Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 13th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Lucky #13. A =
relatively slow week in the world of optimistic news =E2=80=94 just our luc=
k. But as always, if you look hard enough, we humans are always making prog=
ress.=20
Do you enjoy reading the Weekly Dose of Optimism every Friday? Yes [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/6c5e6dc6-4b55-4b63-ac45-99495aacb94f?r=3D9p0gt ], M=
eh [ https://substack.com/redirect/6831b398-9529-400a-b5e6-fdc4f41d2696?r=
=3D9p0gt ], No [ https://substack.com/redirect/37019ea3-e5dc-4b6c-b234-179e=
530bd1ce?r=3D9p0gt ]
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Weekly Dose of Optimism is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 LMNT =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/02bf05c1-5ad3-4dd0-a623-16f4c95bbe6d?r=3D9p=
0gt ]
After years of inconsistency (partially due to busted knees), I=E2=80=99m f=
inally getting into a solid running routine. Just last week, I did over 30 =
miles for the first time in years. And with all of that running, comes a lo=
t of sweating and burnt energy. That=E2=80=99s where LMNT [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/ce2a9bd0-5c74-41fe-90dc-e6ff23c37dea?r=3D9p0gt ] comes in.
LMNT [ https://substack.com/redirect/02bf05c1-5ad3-4dd0-a623-16f4c95bbe6d?r=
=3D9p0gt ] is a tasty electrolyte drink mix that replaces vital electrolyte=
s without sugars and dodgy ingredients found in other sports drinks. It com=
es in a bunch of flavors, is convenient to travel with, and I actually noti=
ce an increase in hydration and recovery after I take it.
As a Not Boring reader, you can get a free Sample Pack (includes 1 packet o=
f every flavor) when you purchase through our link. Support your hydration,=
 recovery, and the Weekly Dose of Optimism by checking out LMNT.
(1) Adnan Syed walks out of Baltimore courthouse after judge overturns his =
2000 murder conviction [ https://substack.com/redirect/51aa04be-d8d7-4a4f-a=
f7a-97887fd6ae16?r=3D9p0gt ]
Alex Mann [ https://substack.com/redirect/97d0c4df-9099-492d-97a1-b59ec43b4=
b33?r=3D9p0gt ] and Lee O. Sanderlin [ https://substack.com/redirect/fa70ba=
2c-62c4-4c21-868e-8b365c6d636f?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Baltimore Sun
Baltimore Circuit Judge Melissa Phinn overturned Syed=E2=80=99s murder conv=
iction in the 1999 killing of Hae Min Lee after prosecutors raised doubts a=
bout his guilty finding because of the revelation of alternative suspects i=
n the homicide and unreliable evidence used against him at trial.
This is a Global Tel Link prepaid newsletter from =E2=80=94 Adnan Syed =E2=
=80=94 a former inmate at a Maryland correctional facility.
I vividly remember the feeling of falling in love with podcasts for the fir=
st time  =E2=80=94 it was 2014 and my mom sent me a text about a new podcas=
t called Serial. Oof, I thought, another NPR-voicey human interest radio ta=
lk show. But for whatever reason, I gave Episode 1 a listen =E2=80=94 and h=
ave been hooked on podcasts ever since.
When listening to Serial, whether you believe Adnan Syed =E2=80=9Cdid it=E2=
=80=9D or not =E2=80=94 I tend to think he is not 100% innocent and was at =
least tangentially involved =E2=80=94 what really sticks out is just how ba=
ckwards the criminal justice system is. Corruption. Incompetency. Bureaucra=
cy. Lack of digitization. Timelines. The whole thing is just really frustra=
ting. And for many people, Serial was the first real glimpse inside the sys=
tem.
In the case of Adnan Syed, the criminal justice system isn=E2=80=99t saying=
 he=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cinnocent," but is basically admitting that the syste=
m didn=E2=80=99t work as designed. The judge (and surprisingly, the Distric=
t Attorney=E2=80=99s Office) recognized this, and overturned the conviction=
 =E2=80=9Cin the interest of justice and fairness.=E2=80=9D Adnan is free.=20
(1a) They=E2=80=99re locked up in D.C. =E2=80=94 and learning how to code f=
rom MIT [ https://substack.com/redirect/ffe1d1d7-c2a3-4719-b168-f71f37401e6=
f?r=3D9p0gt ]
Emily Davies [ https://substack.com/redirect/7872fa62-fbe8-47e0-98f9-1aa34f=
660fb9?r=3D9p0gt ] for The Washington Post, h/t @DSarin91 [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/95aa48ec-80ab-4ee8-aed5-9f1d9557ac91?r=3D9p0gt ]
Crowder, who pleaded guilty to armed robbery in 2020, was one of 16 men who=
 enrolled in the course while detained at the D.C. jail, as part of a new 1=
2-week program from the Educational Justice Institute at MIT. The program, =
called Brave Behind Bars, brought computer science education to the facilit=
y =E2=80=94 adding to the suite of educational services that experts hope w=
ill better prepare detainees for reentry.
Not everyone is as lucky as Adnan. All told, about 2 million people are inc=
arcerated at any given time in the U.S. =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s about the =
size of a large US city, call is Prisonton, with a population somewhere bet=
ween Phoenix and Houston. About 10% of those folks are serving life sentenc=
es, which means that 90% will reenter society. In order to make a life for =
themselves and not circle back into the criminal justice system, former inm=
ates need skills and training to hold down a job. As probably every Not Bor=
ing reader is probably aware, the most in-demand skill in today=E2=80=99s j=
ob market is coding. Programs, such as the one profiled in this Post story,=
 will not solve our engineering deficit, but could provide a strong path to=
 post-incarceration employment for the most ambitious, dedicated, and talen=
ted inmates.
Side note: If you want to learn how to code, too, join Packy [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/d461d2e1-c586-48e1-b03d-9d4d222fb823?r=3D9p0gt ] in takin=
g the 100 Days of Code course on Replit [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f6=
abd17-3868-4462-95c8-4d61e9980f21?r=3D9p0gt ].=20
(2) How to Stop Environmental Review from Harming the Environment [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/ebafb6dc-b63c-4e31-b41e-e1395b45c010?r=3D9p0gt ]
Brian Potter [ https://substack.com/redirect/75d24fda-6346-4bb0-a97f-c16b40=
b080a9?r=3D9p0gt ], Arnab Datta [ https://substack.com/redirect/336ada6b-93=
5e-42bd-9bb8-62b515d81767?r=3D9p0gt ], and Alec Stapp [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/6f14cabe-bbdc-4575-afd7-45abf4d4ce11?r=3D9p0gt ] for Institute f=
or Progress
The NEPA process as it currently exists is slowing down the clean energy tr=
ansition and is long overdue for reform. NEPA imposes massive costs on the =
federal government, drags clean energy projects out for years, and generate=
s uncertainty that stops other projects from ever getting off the ground. W=
ith targeted reforms, Congress can unlock critical clean energy projects th=
at are currently being stifled.
We recently profiled =E2=80=9CThe Case for Abolishing the National Environm=
ental Protection Act [ https://substack.com/redirect/c95b4759-ddf0-46c5-9e1=
f-1e3307b92e47?r=3D9p0gt ]=E2=80=9D in the Weekly Dose of Optimism #11 [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/767e2de8-9813-4d8e-89eb-c5c73b321b13?r=3D9p0gt =
]. This piece, from the Institute for Progress, does a strong job of outlin=
ing how NEPA works and the monetary, time and opportunity costs of its revi=
ews. The authors put forth four potential policy changes that could facilit=
ate the clean energy transition within the constraints of NEPA:
Give clean energy the same regulatory treatment that fossil fuels already r=
eceive
Establish limits on judicial review in actions arising from NEPA
Establish a program to designate =E2=80=9Cenergy security corridors=E2=80=
=9D which would encourage the development of regional energy hubs
Collect comprehensive data on environmental reviews and other permitting is=
sues
Some folks want to abolish NEPA. Others, perhaps more pragmatic, want to es=
tablish policy changes that allow projects to avoid the Act=E2=80=99s more =
deleterious side effects =E2=80=94 but one thing seems to be certain: somet=
hing needs to change if we want to build more clean energy infrastructure f=
aster.
(3) How a Quebec Lithium Mine May Help Make Electric Cars Affordable [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/6f90eff5-9630-45e7-826e-bac88ade4904?r=3D9p0gt ]
Jack Ewing [ https://substack.com/redirect/e0786f21-e285-4312-8a63-79a1072c=
86fd?r=3D9p0gt ] for The New York Times
The mine contains lithium, an indispensable ingredient in electric car batt=
eries that is in short supply. If it opens on schedule early next year, it =
will be the second North American source of that metal, offering hope that =
badly needed raw materials can be extracted and refined close to Canadian, =
U.S. and Mexican auto factories, in line with Biden administration policies=
 that aim to break China=E2=80=99s dominance of the battery supply chain.
A new NYT beat has caught our attention: profiling far-flung, mineral rich =
mines that hold the answer to powering the EV revolution. Whether it=E2=80=
=99s on the ocean floor [ https://substack.com/redirect/9c1bd43e-7597-4518-=
addb-182c047d629a?r=3D9p0gt ], atop a dormant volcano in northern Nevada [ =
https://substack.com/redirect/76b4f5c1-6d58-4ea4-bc73-ac2203fee822?r=3D9p0g=
t ], or in a relatively accessible Quebecois town [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/6f90eff5-9630-45e7-826e-bac88ade4904?r=3D9p0gt ], there seems to be =
a race to discover and revitalize North American lithium mines. We are not =
in a position to say which of these projects will be successful, but it=E2=
=80=99s certainly become clearer that lithium is becoming increasingly impo=
rtant, there is an effort to source it closer to home, and the battery valu=
e chain will continue to attract more and more attention. Policy around bat=
teries, like semiconductors, is a relatively accurate proxy for the tempera=
ture of US-China relations =E2=80=94 and the Biden Administration has been =
turning up the heat on this front.
(4) AlphaFold developers win US$3-million Breakthrough Prize [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/f5af2dce-a37e-4b9f-9e05-9d91cc27759e?r=3D9p0gt ]  [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/f5af2dce-a37e-4b9f-9e05-9d91cc27759e?r=3D9p0gt ]
Zeeya Merali [ https://substack.com/redirect/91412443-6aa0-4cb0-b9a5-fa59b2=
b02d34?r=3D9p0gt ] for Nature
The researchers behind the AlphaFold artificial-intelligence (AI) system ha=
ve won one of this year=E2=80=99s US$3-million Breakthrough prizes =E2=80=
=94 the most lucrative awards in science. Demis Hassabis and John Jumper, b=
oth at DeepMind in London, were recognized for creating the tool that has p=
redicted the 3D structures of almost every known protein on the planet.
The team behind AlphaFold, an AI project from DeepMind which we=E2=80=99ve =
previously written about here [ https://substack.com/redirect/276d1584-a9ef=
-4d7a-a522-af2a1cf195b1?r=3D9p0gt ], here [ https://substack.com/redirect/3=
a4f965d-466e-44ce-97de-ae2adc17f15e?r=3D9p0gt ], here [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/30ae69fb-3651-44b1-a936-7a9c732db18e?r=3D9p0gt ], and here [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/4960d691-6e5e-437d-a4f8-aded99bc872a?r=3D9p0gt ]=
, was awarded $3M USD as one of the winner=E2=80=99s of this year=E2=80=99s=
 Breakthrough Prizes. The Breakthrough Prizes recognize achievements in lif=
e sciences, physics and mathematics =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s the world=E2=80=
=99s largest science prize founded (and funded) by Sergey Brin, Julia and Y=
uri Milner, Priscilla Chan and Mark Zuckerberg. Notably, David Deutsch [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/a3ee90af-9516-4e3e-a280-c741440b0687?r=3D9p0gt =
], whose definition of Optimism we use here at Not Boring [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/d6b1318a-ae75-4b34-9e6d-5978c92075ed?r=3D9p0gt ], was also a=
 winner of this year=E2=80=99s prize for his work on quantum information.
We=E2=80=99re all for good ole=E2=80=99 capitalism and free markets here at=
 Not Boring, but there=E2=80=99s something to be said for using prizes to r=
eward =E2=80=A6 breakthrough =E2=80=A6 fundamental research. Every member o=
f each of the teams that was awarded a Breakthrough Prize this year could l=
ikely have put their big brains towards more personally lucrative career pa=
ths, but society is richer for their work, and we=E2=80=99re glad they secu=
red the bag.=20
(5) Human seasonal influenza under COVID-19 and the potential consequences =
of influenza lineage elimination [ https://substack.com/redirect/463bba31-d=
855-493a-a79b-1ac5aef93976?r=3D9p0gt ]
From Nature, h/t @MattJMcD [ https://substack.com/redirect/de6bc09b-0303-47=
8e-b794-78140f0a1bd1?r=3D9p0gt ]
Who said all that social distancing, mask wearing, travel restrictions, and=
 hand washing was for naught? A new study published in Nature claims that a=
ll of the public health measures put in place to manage the spread of Covid=
-19 have actually dramatically impacted the development of seasonal influen=
za. One strain, B/Yamagata, hasn=E2=80=99t even been detected since April 2=
020. While the medium-to-longer term impact of these developments are unkno=
wn =E2=80=94 meaning, who knows what will happen when the world fully opens=
 up and no one is wearing  mask =E2=80=94 this appears to be a positive sho=
rt-term outcome of all of the lifestyle changes we=E2=80=99ve made over the=
 past two and a half years.
Humans are pulling off some pretty incredible things every week. Whenever y=
ou find examples, share them here [ https://substack.com/redirect/e41a16cd-=
0f64-45fc-bfa6-fadd363cd87b?r=3D9p0gt ] and we=E2=80=99ll feature some in t=
he newsletter.
That=E2=80=99s all for this week =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99ll be back in your inb=
ox 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the weekend.=20
Packy

